nd though. I did not make that decision, only one person did and the blame can go no further. He took the easy way out because it was more appealing to him than working out his problems in life. He left people behind who cared for him and must deal with the consequences of his decision. If the blame can go no further than someone who is not here to answer for their decisions then the answer is simple enough. There is no one to blame. His death becomes meaningless and insignificant with no justice nor hope of contributing a sense of closure.<br>
<br>
My heart goes out to those he left behind who knew him. To his parents and siblings. To his loved ones. I do not think his decision at the time of his death was a sane one. I do not believe that his mother is in a rational state of mind to logically pursue her current course of action. It is not logical to blame a third party for the choices of a single individual. Nor does it make logical sense to place warning labels on anything that you believe is responsible for the death of anyone. If I knew a product would flat out kill one person out of every billion who used it I would not support that product and I would do what I could to support it being banned. I would not insist on the half effort of warning labels. I would not wrap a loaded gun up in police tape and then still allow a child to handle it. However, the main element that everyone seems to be over looking is that Suicide is not a criminal act. It is simply a Bad Choice. If we where to arrest everyone who ever made a bad choice that put themselves into harms way either through the results of mental illness or simple stupidity. There would not be a free person on the face of this planet. As parents our job is to teach our children to cope with what life deals out to them and hope for the best. There are no instructions on how to do this, there is not a fool proof way and there is no one to blame if our children fail at this task. All we can do is hope for a best effort, help where we can and pray for a lot of luck. When all is said and done our lives are either made or broken by the decisions that we make. Let us all bring meaning to this tragedy by not pointing finger but by taking note and remembering an individual has made a choice. <br>
